"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942673","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-07-19","<p>This information requested is not available.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-07-19T16:39:36.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942673/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942673/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-07-16","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of face-to-face appointments have been conducted to verify a claimant's identity; and what the average waiting time was from the point of claiming Universal Credit to receiving a face-to-face assessment in order to verify a claimants identity since the introduction of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","164374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942674","Home Office","false","2018-07-19","<p>Afghan interpreters who qualify to come to the UK under the relocation schemes are able to bring qualifying dependant family members with them. To date, around 400 former Afghan interpreters have relocated to the UK with their families making around 1,100 people in total.</p><p>The Home Office has committed to looking at what can be done to improve the process for Afghan interpreters to bring to the UK those otherwise eligible dependents who did not travel and who remain in Afghanistan.</p><p>We do not publish a breakdown of data relating to visa applications received from family members of those resettled under the ex-gratia scheme.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-07-19T14:56:02.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942674/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942674/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-07-16","Visas: Afghanistan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many successful spousal visa applications there have been for the (a) spouses and (b) children of Afghan interpreters who relocated to the UK under the Government's Redundancy Scheme.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","164375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942675","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-07-19","<p>The Common Rulebook will include rules necessary to provide for frictionless trade at the border. The rules have been developed over the last 30 years or more to reflect the connected nature of the UK and EU economies and respond to emerging risks. The UK has long advocated a convergence of rules and standards for goods, which are relatively stable, and therefore consider the adoption of a common rulebook is in both the UK’s and EU’s interests.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In our negotiations with the EU we will ensure that the scope of the common rule book is limited to those areas without which there would be friction at the border.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2018-07-19T15:33:06.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942675/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942675/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-07-16","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to sub-paragraph 7(a) on page 14 of the White Paper, The future relationship between the UK and the EU, Cm. 9353, published on 12 July 2018, which items of EU legislation adopted over the last 30 years have made changes to the rules included in the definition of the common rulebook for goods, including agri-food, covering only those rules necessary to provide for frictionless trade at the border.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","164338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942676","Department for Education","false","2018-07-19","<p>I refer the hon. Member for Newcastle upon Tyne North to the answer I gave on 23 April 2018 to Question <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2018-04-18/136545/" target="_blank">136545</a>.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-07-19T16:38:27.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942676/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942676/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-07-16","Pupils: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 23 April 2018 to Question 136545 on Pupils: Disadvantaged, and the oral contribution of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Education of 14 May 2018, Official Report, column 8, what his Department's policy is on the review of the educational outcomes of children in need of help or support aged 16 and 17.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","164429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942677","Treasury","false","2018-07-19","<p>Under EU law, a standard rate of VAT must be applied to e-publications. Although Member States are discussing a legislative proposal to allow the same VAT rate to apply to e-publications as apply to physical publications, this is yet to be agreed.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-07-19T15:49:28.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942677/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942677/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942677/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-07-16","Electronic Publishing: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has plans to reduce VAT on digital editions of magazines, books and newspapers.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","164430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942678","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-07-20","<p>There was no cost to the public purse for the Tempest concept model unveiled at the Farnborough International Airshow.</p>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson",,"2018-07-20T13:26:55.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942678/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942678/answer","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942678/answer/previousversion/70572","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","11","Defence","Defence","2018-07-16","Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the cost to the public purse was of the combat aircraft concept model he unveiled at Farnborough International Air show in July 2018.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","164364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942679","Cabinet Office","false","2018-07-19","<p>There is not currently a standardised cross-government pay scale for Policy Officers as pay for this role, like all others in delegated grades (AA-G6), is delegated to departments.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-07-19T11:50:33.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942679/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942679/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942679/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-07-16","Government Departments: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Cabinet Office, whether there are standardised cross-department pay scales for the post of policy officer in each Government Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","164510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942680","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-25","<p>As of 12 July, 2018, fourteen publicly-owned buildings (including schools and hospitals) have failed large-scale system tests on their cladding systems. One building has now completed the remediation process, including removal and replacement of its aluminium composite material cladding. The other building owners are working with the relevant fire and rescue service and other specialists to consider remedial work, and are taking account of building users’ needs when they do so. We are not aware of any high-rise care homes with aluminium composite material cladding systems.</p><p>We are working with the Department of Health and Social Care, NHS Improvement and Department for Education to ensure that appropriate remediation steps are being taken on public buildings.</p><p> </p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-07-25T15:51:34.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942680/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942680/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-07-16","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether the Government plans to require the removal of combustible cladding and insulation from (a) schools, (b) care homes and (c) hospitals.","false","Biography information for Karen Lee","Lincoln","Karen Lee","164527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942681","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-24","<p>Dame Judith Hackitt’s review recommended that test methods and standards should be regularly reviewed in order to drive continuous improvement. The Government has invited views on the Dame Judith’s findings and recommendations, and will set out an implementation plan in the autumn.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-07-24T16:33:07.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942681/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942681/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942681/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-07-16","Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what plans his Department has to introduce a more robust regulatory framework for fire conditions during tests of combustibility of materials.","false","Biography information for Karen Lee","Lincoln","Karen Lee","164528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942682","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-25","<p>The latest data available was published on 12 July 2018. Of the 159 social sector buildings that have combinations of Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding and insulation judged to have failed the large-scale tests 114 or 72 per cent have started the process of remediation. Of these, 13 buildings have finished remediation. Of the 301 private sector residential buildings with cladding systems that are unlikely to meet current Building Regulations guidance, local authorities have told us about plans for remediating 77 buildings. Of these, 23 buildings have started remediation, of which 4 have completed.</p><p>A new minister-chaired taskforce has been established to oversee the remediation of private sector buildings with aluminium composite material cladding systems. The taskforce is charged with ensuring that remediation plans are put in place swiftly across all private sector buildings with aluminium composite material cladding systems, and addressing any barriers or identifying any additional support required to achieve this.</p><p>The consultation on banning the use of combustible materials in the external walls of high-rise residential buildings closes on 14 August. Consultation responses will be analysed over the summer, with the outcome of the consultation to follow.</p><p> </p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-07-25T15:51:10.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942682/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942682/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-07-16","Fire Prevention: High Rise Flats","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what the timetable is for (a) the remedial work on all high-rise buildings with combustible cladding and (b) the implementation of a ban on combustible cladding.","false","Biography information for Karen Lee","Lincoln","Karen Lee","164529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942683","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-07-24","<p>The number of departmental officials who work on either National Minimum Wage policy or on enforcement policy has been approximately ten full time equivalent (FTE) members of staff in each of the years from 2010-11 to 2017-18. This an estimated figure based on the average across the calendar year.</p><p> </p><p>Furthermore, we are committed to cracking down on employers who break the National Minimum Wage law. This is why this Government continues to invest heavily in minimum wage enforcement, increasing the budget to £26.3 million for 2018/19, up from £13 million in 2015/16.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-07-24T13:23:01.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942683/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942683/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-07-16","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many officials in his and the predecessor Department worked on the Government’s national minimum wage application and enforcement policies in each year from 2010-11 to 2017-18; and what the current staffing level of that policy area is.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","164302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942684","Home Office","false","2018-07-24","<p>Dame Judith Hackitt’s report calls for major reform of the regulatory system and for culture change across the construction and fire safety industries. The government agreed with the broad principles of the report and committed to bring forward legislation.</p><p>The Home Office and Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government are working with partners to consider the detail of Dame Judith’s recommendations and will set out an implementation plan in the autumn.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-07-24T15:33:46.223Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942684/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942684/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-07-16","Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether he has made an assessment of the capacity of his Department's workforce to produce a new statutory fire regulatory framework.","false","Biography information for Karen Lee","Lincoln","Karen Lee","164530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942685","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-24","<p>A number of staff across the Department contributed to the work on the consultation into banning combustible cladding and the Independent Review of Building Regulations and Fire Safety. The Department does not hold information centrally on the staff time or costs taken to prepare the consultation or carry out the review. Dame Judith Hackitt chaired the Independent Review of Building Regulations and Fire Safety on a pro bono basis – she was not remunerated and only received reimbursement for exceptional travel expenses.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-07-24T16:32:32.83Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942685/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942685/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-07-16","High Rise Flats: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what the cost to the public purse has been of the (a) consultation into the banning combustible cladding and (b) the Independent Review of Building Regulations and Fire Safety led by Dame Judith Hackitt Review.","false","Biography information for Karen Lee","Lincoln","Karen Lee","164531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942686","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-07-24","<p>There have been no formal contract changes made to the contracts with Amey following the HMP Liverpool inspection report. Our focus continues to be securing improvements to the operational delivery of the contracts with Amey through strengthened contract management and oversight.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-07-24T14:56:21.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942686/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942686/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942686/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-07-16","Amey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 4 July 2018 to Question 157827 on Amey, what changes his Department made to the contracts with Amey after they were reset following the HMP Liverpool inspection report in January 2018.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","164494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942687","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-07-24","<p>Additional funding has not been allocated to the core fixed fee work elements of the Amey contracts after the HMP Liverpool inspection report. Nevertheless, the volume of variable fee work at HMP Liverpool has increased over the last few months as the outstanding maintenance issues at the prison are addressed.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-07-24T14:58:11.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942687/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942687/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942687/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-07-16","Amey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 4 July 2018 to Question 157827 on Amey, whether additional funding was allocated to Amey after contracts with the company were reset after the HMP Liverpool inspection report in January 2018.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","164495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942688","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-07-23","<p>Once an agreement is reached between the UK and the EU on the shape of the future relationship, there is no reason to expect that either party will break the commitments the UK and the EU have made to each other. However, as is normal in international agreements, the UK and the EU will still need to agree on what should happen if one party is in breach of the agreements.</p><p><strong><br></strong>As the White Paper says, suspension measures should be rarely used, and when used should be limited, with priority given to those non-compliance measures which cause least damage to the functioning of the agreement. A financial penalty is another potential non-compliance measure. By way of example, the US has included financial compensation in eleven free trade agreements, including US-Australia and US-South Korea. Any non-compliance measures taken should end once any non-compliance has ended and where there is ongoing non-compliance measures should be renewed by notifying the Joint Committee.<strong> </strong></p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","164340 ; 164933 ; 164934","2018-07-23T16:53:28.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942688/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942688/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942688/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-07-16","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 47 on page 94 of the White Paper, The future relationship between the United Kingdom and the European Union, Cm. 9593, published on 12 July 2018, what those financial penalties are.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","164339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942689","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-07-23","<p>Once an agreement is reached between the UK and the EU on the shape of the future relationship, there is no reason to expect that either party will break the commitments the UK and the EU have made to each other. However, as is normal in international agreements, the UK and the EU will still need to agree on what should happen if one party is in breach of the agreements.</p><p><strong><br></strong>As the White Paper says, suspension measures should be rarely used, and when used should be limited, with priority given to those non-compliance measures which cause least damage to the functioning of the agreement. A financial penalty is another potential non-compliance measure. By way of example, the US has included financial compensation in eleven free trade agreements, including US-Australia and US-South Korea. Any non-compliance measures taken should end once any non-compliance has ended and where there is ongoing non-compliance measures should be renewed by notifying the Joint Committee.<strong> </strong></p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","164339 ; 164933 ; 164934","2018-07-23T16:53:28.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942689/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942689/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942689/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-07-16","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 47 on page 94 of the White Paper, The future relationship between the United Kingdom and the European Union, Cm. 9593, published on 12 July 2018, what the obligations are which could be suspended.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","164340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942690","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-07-23","<p>The institutional provisions set out in the White Paper will ensure accountability in relation to the agreements. Parliamentary scrutiny is integral to ensuring accountability and the Government recognises the expertise in the existing scrutiny structures in the Commons and the Lords. The UK Parliament will have a role in overseeing and scrutinising any proposals that relate to ongoing cooperation between the UK and the EU under the agreements. The Government will bring forward further legislation, as appropriate, to give effect to the future relationship in the UK.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","164334 ; 164936 ; 164939","2018-07-23T16:44:00.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942690/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942690/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942690/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-07-16","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 55 of Chapter Four of the White Paper, The future relationship between the United Kingdom and the European Union, Cm. 9593, published on 12 July 2018, what proposals the Government plans to bring before the House in respect of that parliamentary scrutiny.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","164341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942691","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-07-23","<p>A full reply was sent by email to the hon. Member for Slough on 19.7.18.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2018-07-23T16:24:48.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942691/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942691/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942691/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-07-16","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if she will arrange for a response to be sent to the email of 23 May 2018 from the hon. Member for Slough sent on behalf of a constituent to her Department's Operations Correspondence Team and subsequently forwarded by that team on 24 May 2018 to the Berkshire, Buckinghamshire and Oxfordshire Operations Correspondence Team.","false","Biography information for Mr Tanmanjeet Singh Dhesi","Slough","Mr Tanmanjeet Singh Dhesi","164524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942692","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-07-25","<p>UK courts would pay due regard to CJEU case law in only those areas where the UK continued to apply a common rulebook. The common rulebook will cover goods including agri-food, where those rules are necessary to provide for frictionless trade at the border.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Where the UK agrees to retain a common rulebook with the EU, it will be important for businesses and citizens here and in the EU that those areas are interpreted and applied consistently. The UK has therefore proposed that it would commit by treaty that its courts would pay due regard to CJEU case law, insofar as this was relevant to the matter before them. This is a recognition of legal fact - no other court can bind the EU on the meaning of EU law.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>However, these rights would be enforced in the UK by UK courts and in the EU by EU courts.</p><p>No longer will courts in the UK be able to refer cases to the CJEU, including in cases involving individuals and businesses. And at present, the UK is bound by all CJEU decisions - hundreds of decisions every year which have direct effect in the UK, whether the case originated in the UK or not. This will no longer be the case.</p><p> </p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","164932","2018-07-25T15:53:59.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942692/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942692/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942692/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-07-16","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph of Chapter Four of the White Paper, The future relationship between the United Kingdom and the European Union, Cm. 9593, published on 12 July 2018, which the rules are which would be interpreted by the Court of Justice of the European Union under the proposals there set out.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","164342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942693","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-07-25","<p>The proposed role of the Joint Committee is set out in Chapter 4 of the White Paper. It will be responsible for the functioning of the overarching institutional framework, which will encompass most of our agreements with the EU. It will do so through regular and structured dialogue, and by making decisions in order to manage any issues, and mitigate any disputes that might arise, including where significant divergences in interpretation had been identified.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>If a dispute were to arise due to a significant divergence, a formal dispute could be raised in the Joint Committee. In some areas, it may be escalated to independent arbitration if a resolution cannot be reached in the Joint Committee.</p><p> </p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","164929 ; 164930","2018-07-25T15:52:33.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942693/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942693/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-07-16","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 35 of Chapter Four of the White Paper, The future relationship between the United Kingdom and the European Union, Cm. 9593, published on 12 July 2018, which the actions are that the Joint Committee will be empowered to take in the event of significant divergences between the interpretation of agreements by the courts of the UK and the EU.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","164343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942694","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-07-23","<p>This Department takes puppy smuggling extremely seriously.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Chief Veterinary Officer (CVO) has raised cases of abuse of the Pet Travel Scheme, based on evidence from UK enforcement bodies, with those authorities in the relevant Member States. This includes writing to the CVO’s Polish counterpart in October 2016 and Hungarian counterpart in November 2016 to notify them of the identification of several non-complaint puppies originating from their countries, which had been seized on entry to the UK. The CVO at the time of publication also had a number of exchanges with his Lithuanian counterpart.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-07-23T14:08:52.96Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942694/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942694/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942694/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-07-16","Dogs: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the report Puppy smuggling, a tragedy ignored, published by Dogs Trust in July 2017, whether his Department has made representations to the countries cited in that report.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","164478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942695","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-07-20","<p>We are consulting with the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy as well as industry partners and subject matter experts on the development of a Combat Air Skills Index which will form an important element of the acquisition programme. As stated in the strategy, I will provide an annual update to Parliament on progress in implementation.</p>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson",,"2018-07-20T13:25:44.72Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942695/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942695/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942695/answer","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942695/answer/previousversion/70568","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","11","Defence","Defence","2018-07-16","Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to page 31, paragraph 51 of the Combat Air Strategy, published in July 2018, when his Department plans to launch a Combat Air Skills Index.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","164365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942696","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-07-20","<p>The National Value Framework is already outlined in Chapter 4 of the Combat Air Strategy.</p>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson",,"2018-07-20T13:26:25.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942696/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942696/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942696/answer","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942696/answer/previousversion/70564","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","11","Defence","Defence","2018-07-16","Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to page 31, paragraph 54 of the Combat Air Strategy, when he plans to publish the National Value Framework.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","164366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942697","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-07-23","<p>In line with the Ministry of Defence (MOD)'s 'whole force concept' approach, the acquisition team will be a multidisciplinary organisation, drawing on talent from across Defence. Programmes of this nature necessarily need to evolve over time along with the size and composition of the Team, but the core leadership group to initiate the acquisition will comprise two Air Force officers and three civil servants. They will lead and draw on the significant expertise of the rest of the MOD's Strategic Programmes team, Head Office, Team Tempest, DSTL, Defence Equipment and Support, other Government Departments and industry.</p>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson",,"2018-07-23T16:06:30.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942697/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942697/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942697/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-07-16","Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to paragraph 46 on page 30 of the Combat Air Strategy, published on 16 July 2018. how many (a) civil servants and (b) armed forces personnel will be in the Combat Air Strategy acquisition team.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","164367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942698","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-07-20","<p>Chapters 2 and 5 of the Combat Air Strategy outline the expected behaviours and performance of Team Tempest. These, along with the technical outcomes delivered, will be used to inform the acquisition programme.</p>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson",,"2018-07-20T13:21:30.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942698/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942698/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942698/answer","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942698/answer/previousversion/70561","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","11","Defence","Defence","2018-07-16","Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to page 19, paragraph 27 of the Combat Air Strategy what the criteria will be for assessing the performance of Team Tempest.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","164368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942699","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-07-20","<p>Tempest is the name given to the capability concept unveiled on 16 July 2018 at the Farnborough International Air Show. The Combat Air Strategy makes clear that the UK intends to take a measured and collaborative approach to delivery of our future capability. The name of the next UK developed combat aircraft will be decided as part of the acquisition and partnering timeline set out in the Strategy.</p>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson",,"2018-07-20T13:20:51.07Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942699/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942699/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942699/answer","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942699/answer/previousversion/70557","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","11","Defence","Defence","2018-07-16","Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to page 19, paragraph 27 of the Combat Air Strategy, whether the name Tempest will be given to the next UK-developed combat aircraft.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","164369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942700","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-07-23","<p>The Prime Minister has always been clear that in leaving the EU, we will bring about an end to the jurisdiction of the CJEU in the UK. The proposal set out in the White Paper delivers on that commitment. No longer will courts in the UK be able to refer cases to the CJEU, nor will the CJEU be able to arbitrate disputes between the UK and the EU. The CJEU will no longer have the power to make laws for the UK and the principles of direct effect and of the supremacy of EU law will no longer apply in the UK.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Instead, rights will be enforced in the UK by UK courts and in the EU by EU courts. Where the UK agrees to retain a common rulebook with the EU, it will be important for businesses and citizens here and in the EU that those areas are interpreted and applied consistently. The UK would commit by treaty that its courts would pay due regard to CJEU case law, insofar as this was relevant to the matter before them. This is a recognition of legal fact - no other court can bind the EU on the meaning of EU law. Of course, this is in practice what our Courts would do anyway, and are free to do with the judgements of foreign courts. Importantly, UK courts would not be able to make preliminary references to the CJEU as once the UK has left the EU, such references would no longer be appropriate or necessary.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","164337","2018-07-23T16:48:17.533Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942700/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942700/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942700/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-07-16","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 35 of Chapter Four of the White Paper, The future relationship between the United Kingdom and the European Union, Cm. 9593, published on 12 July 2018, what the difference is between the current prevailing legal principles relating to the Court of Justice of the European Union and the obligation there envisaged on paying due regard to EU case law.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","164344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942701","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-07-23","<p>The industrial prime contractors who form Team Tempest, alongside Government, are working closely with the UK's small and medium enterprises (and associated subject matter experts), academia and the supply chain to maximise the values laid out in the Combat Air Strategy. The Strategy makes clear that industry must leverage the best processes and technologies wherever they are found in the global supply chain and this includes small and medium enterprises.</p>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson",,"2018-07-23T16:07:00.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942701/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942701/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942701/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-07-16","Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to page 19, paragraph 26 of the Combat Air Strategy, whether there are any SMEs in Team Tempest.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","164370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942702","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-07-23","<p>The Combat Air Strategy makes clear that Government is investing nearly £2 billion over 10 years in the Future Combat Air Systems Technology Initiative. This will mature the technologies of the future, develop UK Intellectual Property and will include those skills necessary to sustain UK operational advantage and freedom of action.</p>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson",,"2018-07-23T16:05:46.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942702/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942702/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942702/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-07-16","Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to page 15, paragraph 13 of the Combat Air Strategy, how much investment his Department plans to provide to key UK design engineering skills and a means to generate UK Intellectual Property.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","164371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942703","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-07-23","<p>This Government has been clear that the UK will maintain high environmental, climate change, and labour standards once it has left the EU. In recognition of these ambitious, domestic choices, the Government proposes that as the UK leaves the EU, both parties should commit to the non-regression of environmental and labour standards.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Our climate change agenda is set out in domestic law, and our commitments are more ambitious than those that arise from our current obligations under EU law. The UK will maintain its world-leading climate standards after we leave the EU.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Across all three areas, the exact details will be subject to negotiation.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In future, all laws in the UK will be legislated for by Parliament or a devolved legislative and subject to appropriate oversight and scrutiny.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","164346 ; 164347 ; 164348 ; 164349 ; 164350","2018-07-23T16:50:06.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942703/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942703/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942703/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-07-16","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 7 of page 14 of the White Paper, The future relationship between the United Kingdom and the European Union, Cm. 9593, published on 12 July 2018, what it is proposed should be included in the non-regression provisions; and what level of detail will be specified in such provisions.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","164345"
