"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942709","Department for Education","false","2018-07-19","<p>I am working with a number of partners in the Higher Education sector in the development of guidance. This includes the National Union of Students, who represent the majority of student unions including those with Israel societies.</p><p>I have asked the Equality and Human Rights Commission (EHRC) to lead the guidance. As part of their evidence base the EHRC are considering the Joint Committee on Human Rights’ inquiry into freedom of speech in universities. The inquiry heard evidence from representatives of the Union of Jewish Students and university Israel societies.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-07-19T14:04:53.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942709/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942709/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942709/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-07-16","Universities: Freedom of Expression","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the summit held on 3 May 2018 to discuss the preparation of new guidance to promote freedom of speech at universities, and the Government response to the Eighth Report of the Joint Committee on Human Rights, Freedom of Speech in Universities, HC 1279, what plans he has to ensure that representatives of University Israel Societies are involved in the discussions on freedom of speech.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","164259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942710","Department for International Development","false","2018-07-19","<p>The UK Government deplores any act of incitement to violence. Our partnership with the Palestinian Authority (PA) includes a commitment from the Palestinian leadership to adhere to the principle of non-violence and to tackle language and avoid actions that could incite violence or hatred. During my most recent visit to the Occupied Palestinian Territories in May 2018, I personally led this year’s high level annual meeting as part of our annual dialogue with the PA where I challenged the PA on a number of issues such as incitement. The UK continues to urge the Palestinian leadership to uphold this principle of non-violence.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-07-19T17:05:09.943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942710/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942710/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942710/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-07-16","Palestinians: Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to her Department's Memorandum of Understanding with the Palestinian Authority (PA), what discussions her Department has had with the PA on the erection of a billboard in April 2018, organised and sponsored by the PA funded Palestinian Prisoners' Club, honouring 17 Palestinian terrorists.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","164260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942711","Department for International Development","false","2018-07-19","<p>Our sustained support to the PA means that we have a close and robust relationship with senior PA Ministers. I have raised issues of incitement in the education sector in a number of recent conversations with the PA Minister for Education and Higher Education, most recently when I met with the PA during my visit to the Occupied Palestinian Territories in May 2018. Our partnership with the Palestinian Authority (PA) includes a commitment from the Palestinian leadership to adhere to the principle of non-violence and to tackle language and avoid actions that could incite violence or hatred. The UK continues to urge the Palestinian leadership to uphold this principle.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-07-19T17:06:31.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942711/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942711/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942711/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-07-16","Palestinians: Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to her Department's Memorandum of Understanding with the Palestinian Authority (PA), what discussions her Department has had with the PA on the naming of a PA Ministry of Education branch volleyball championship in May 2018 after Abd Al-Jaber Abd Al-Qaeder Khaled, who attempted to carry out a suicide bombing attack in 2002.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","164261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942712","Department for International Development","false","2018-07-19","<p>The UK Government deplores any act of incitement to violence. Our partnership with the Palestinian Authority (PA) includes a commitment from the Palestinian leadership to adhere to the principle of non-violence and to tackle language and avoid actions that could incite violence or hatred. During my most recent visit to the Occupied Palestinian Territories in May 2018, I personally led this year’s high level annual meeting as part of our annual dialogue with the PA where I challenged the PA on a number of issues such as incitement. The UK continues to urge the Palestinian leadership to uphold this principle of non-violence.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-07-19T17:07:27.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942712/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942712/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942712/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-07-16","Palestinians: Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to her Department's Memorandum of Understanding with the Palestinian Authority (PA), what discussions her Department has had with the PA on the description on official PA TV on 17 February 2018 of the Nimr Mahmoud Ahmed Al-Jamal, responsible for the murder of three Israelis, as a martyr who ascended to heaven.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","164262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942713","Department for International Development","false","2018-07-19","<p>The UK Government deplores any act of incitement to violence. Our partnership with the Palestinian Authority (PA) includes a commitment from the Palestinian leadership to adhere to the principle of non-violence and to tackle language and avoid actions that could incite violence or hatred. During my most recent visit to the Occupied Palestinian Territories in May 2018, I personally led this year’s high level annual meeting as part of our annual dialogue with the PA where I challenged the PA on a number of issues such as incitement. The UK continues to urge the Palestinian leadership to uphold this principle of non-violence.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-07-19T17:08:14.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942713/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942713/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942713/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-07-16","Palestinians: Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to her Department's Memorandum of Understanding with the Palestinian Authority (PA), what discussions her Department has had with the PA on the broadcast on 3 February 2018 on the official PA radio station, The Voice of Palestine, of a poem featuring lyrics stating that Palestine is etched on the heart of the foetus, a proud martyr in his mother's womb.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","164263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942714","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-19","<p>The Government's position on Lough Foyle and Carlingford Lough has not changed. The regulation of activities in Lough Foyle is the responsibility of the Loughs Agency, a cross-border body established under the Belfast Agreement of 1998. We remain fully committed to these arrangements and continue to work closely with the Irish Government over improvements to the management of the Loughs. British and Irish officials last met in October 2017 when a number of issues were discussed including the Loughs, and the management of aquaculture in them, and they have been in regular contact since.</p><p>Like the Irish Government, we do not anticipate these issues forming part of the negotiations over the UK's exit from the European Union. Indeed, we have both publically stated on numerous occasions that the issue of the management of the Loughs is distinct from, and will not form part of, any Brexit negotiation.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","164299 ; 164300","2018-07-19T16:13:30.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942714/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942714/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942714/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-07-16","Carlingford Lough and Lough Foyle: Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what progress he has made with his Irish counterparts on concluding an agreement on the management of agriculture activities in (a) Lough Foylet and (b) Carlingford Lough; what the remaining matters are to be resolved; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","164298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942715","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-19","<p>The Government's position on Lough Foyle and Carlingford Lough has not changed. The regulation of activities in Lough Foyle is the responsibility of the Loughs Agency, a cross-border body established under the Belfast Agreement of 1998. We remain fully committed to these arrangements and continue to work closely with the Irish Government over improvements to the management of the Loughs. British and Irish officials last met in October 2017 when a number of issues were discussed including the Loughs, and the management of aquaculture in them, and they have been in regular contact since.</p><p>Like the Irish Government, we do not anticipate these issues forming part of the negotiations over the UK's exit from the European Union. Indeed, we have both publically stated on numerous occasions that the issue of the management of the Loughs is distinct from, and will not form part of, any Brexit negotiation.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","164298 ; 164300","2018-07-19T16:13:30.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942715/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942715/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942715/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-07-16","Carlingford Lough and Lough Foyle: Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many meetings he has held with his Irish counterparts to discuss a management agreement for agriculture activities for (a) Lough Foyle and (b) Carlingford Lough in the last 12 months; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","164299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942716","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-19","<p>The Government's position on Lough Foyle and Carlingford Lough has not changed. The regulation of activities in Lough Foyle is the responsibility of the Loughs Agency, a cross-border body established under the Belfast Agreement of 1998. We remain fully committed to these arrangements and continue to work closely with the Irish Government over improvements to the management of the Loughs. British and Irish officials last met in October 2017 when a number of issues were discussed including the Loughs, and the management of aquaculture in them, and they have been in regular contact since.</p><p>Like the Irish Government, we do not anticipate these issues forming part of the negotiations over the UK's exit from the European Union. Indeed, we have both publically stated on numerous occasions that the issue of the management of the Loughs is distinct from, and will not form part of, any Brexit negotiation.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","164298 ; 164299","2018-07-19T16:13:30.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942716/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942716/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942716/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-07-16","Carlingford Lough and Lough Foyle: Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether a management agreement with the Republic of Ireland on agriculture activities in relation to (a) Lough Foyle and (b) Carlingford Lough will be in place when the UK leaves the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","164300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942717","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-07-23","<p>We are exploring all options to ensure trade in the European Eel can be maintained. This includes compiling the scientific evidence that may be needed to ensure that trade in Lough Neagh eels is compatible with the requirements of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species post EU exit.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-07-23T15:45:33.593Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942717/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942717/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/942717/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-07-16","Eels: Lough Neagh","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Secretary of State is taking to protect the eel industry in Lough Weagh when the UK leaves the EU in March 2019; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","164301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940630","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-07-17","<p>The UK and EU have reached agreement on an implementation period that will operate from 30 March 2019 until 31 December 2020. During this period, market access to the EU will continue on current terms, enabling businesses to trade as now.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-07-17T16:43:33.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940630/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940630/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940630/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-07-13","Business","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to provide stability for businesses as the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Marsha De Cordova","Battersea","Marsha De Cordova","906491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940634","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-07-23","<p>This information is not collected centrally and is only available at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Women’s centres offer support to women with a wide range of issues and needs, not all of whom have been referred by or have come into contact with the Criminal Justice System.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2018-07-23T14:01:03.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940634/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940634/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-07-13","Women's Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many women were served by each women's centre in each year between 2010 and 2017.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","163802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940635","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-07-23","<p>The latest evidence indicates that increased use of ROTL for suitable offenders is linked to a small but statistically significant reduction in rates of proven reoffending and frequency of reoffences. The evidence also shows that compliance rates with ROTL are very high. The criteria for success in improving the use of ROTL will be developed alongside the policy but the objective is to help to reduce reoffending whilst maintaining high compliance.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2018-07-23T14:00:42.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940635/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940635/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940635/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-07-13","Offenders: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what criteria his Department will use to assess the success of the review of current rules regarding release on temporary licence in the Female Offenders Strategy, published in June 2018.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","163803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940636","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-07-23","<p>I can confirm the £5m figure announced in the Female Offender Strategy will be funded through the Ministry of Justice’s existing departmental budget and additional funding allocated to the Home Office in the Spring Budget 2017 to support victims of domestic abuse.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2018-07-23T14:00:01.843Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940636/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940636/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940636/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-07-13","Offenders: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the £5 million of funding announced in the Female Offender Strategy for community provision for women will come from (a) additional resources or (b) the existing Departmental budget.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","163804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940637","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-07-19","<p>The Department is aware of research showing increases in attendances at hospital and in primary care for self-harm amongst young women and continues to review a wide range of research to inform evidence-based policy development on mental health.</p><p> </p><p>In 2017, the Department expanded the scope of the National Suicide Prevention Strategy to include addressing self-harm as an issue in its own right. The Department also continues to fund the Multi-Centre Study of Self-Harm which analyses data on people presenting at hospital for self-harm and identifies long-term trends.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is investing at record levels to transform mental health services which includes making available £1.4 billion to improve access to children and young people’s mental health services. We are investing up to an additional £300 million to deliver the proposals set out in the joint health and education Green Paper ‘Transforming children and young people’s mental health provision: a green paper’.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Government is investing £247 million to roll-out liaison mental health teams in accident and emergency departments by 2020 to ensure that people who present at hospital with mental health problems get the appropriate care and treatment they need. Liaison mental health teams are well placed to deal with presentations for self-harm and to ensure that people receive a psychosocial assessment of their mental health needs to prevent further self-harming.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-07-19T14:55:10.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940637/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940637/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940637/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-07-13","Self Harm: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the implications for his polices of reports from the British Medical Association that self-harm among teenage girls has increased by 68 per cent in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","163806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940638","Home Office","false","2018-07-17","<p>As set out in paragraph 6.12 of the Statement of Intent on the EU Settlement Scheme published on 21 June 2018, provision in the Immigration Rules will be made for a non-EU citizen who is the primary carer of a British citizen in the UK and who currently derives a right of residence from wider EU law (a Zambrano carer).</p><p>Further details will be provided in due course on the new status which will be available to them. The Home Office has no plans to allocate funding in this area.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","163798","2018-07-17T16:31:54.83Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940638/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940638/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940638/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-07-13","Immigration: Carers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what his policy is on the right to reside in the UK of carers with Ruiz-Zambrano status who are nationals of countries outside of the EU after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","163797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940639","Home Office","false","2018-07-17","<p>As set out in paragraph 6.12 of the Statement of Intent on the EU Settlement Scheme published on 21 June 2018, provision in the Immigration Rules will be made for a non-EU citizen who is the primary carer of a British citizen in the UK and who currently derives a right of residence from wider EU law (a Zambrano carer).</p><p>Further details will be provided in due course on the new status which will be available to them. The Home Office has no plans to allocate funding in this area.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","163797","2018-07-17T16:31:54.877Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940639/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940639/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940639/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-07-13","Immigration: Carers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what funding his Department plans to allocate to British children of carers residing in the UK under Zambrano status after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","163798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940640","Treasury","false","2018-07-23","<p>The Government is committed to robustly tackling false self-employment. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) will investigate any evidence suggesting companies may have misclassified individuals for tax purposes. In these cases, HMRC will identify the facts and take steps to ensure the right tax and National Insurance contributions are paid.</p><p> </p><p>Where the off-payroll working rules (IR35) apply, employer’s National Insurance contributions are payable. In April 2017, the Government introduced reform to IR35 for the public sector meaning responsibility shifted for determining whether the rules apply, from the individual’s own company to the public sector body engaging them. Early tax receipts are broadly in line with what was expected from the reform and the forecast of what the measure would raise.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-07-23T15:53:39.63Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940640/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940640/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940640/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-07-13","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect on revenue to the public purse of corporations hiring workers as self-employed to circumvent their employer’s national insurance contributions and workers’ rights liabilities as a result of changes to IR35 regulations.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","163769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940641","Department for Education","false","2018-07-23","<p>Students from the lowest-income households who started their courses this year have access to the largest ever amounts of cash-in-hand support for their living costs.</p><p> </p><p>Disabled Students’ Allowances (DSAs) are not means-tested so applicants are not required to submit evidence of their family income. DSAs are not intended to cover study costs any student might have, nor disability-related expenditure a student would incur if they were not studying in higher education. The £200 contribution was introduced as computers are a mainstream cost for all students and it is right therefore that students eligible for DSAs should contribute towards the cost of their DSAs-recommended computer equipment.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-07-23T11:21:55.14Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940641/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940641/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940641/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-07-13","Disabled Students' Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the £200 contribution for Disabled Students’ Allowance equipment on the take-up of that allowance on students from low income families.","false","Biography information for Marsha De Cordova","Battersea","Marsha De Cordova","163822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940642","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-07-19","<p>This Government has been clear that the UK will maintain high environmental standards once it has left the EU. The UK is party to numerous Multilateral Environmental Agreements, and the UK is committed to upholding its international obligations under these agreements after it leaves the EU.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In recognition of these ambitious, domestic choices, the Government proposes that as the UK leaves the EU, both parties should commit to the non-regression of environmental standards. The exact details of this will be subject to negotiation.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2018-07-19T15:04:03.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940642/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940642/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940642/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-07-13","Environment Protection: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 108(c) of the White Paper, The future relationship between the UK and the EU, Cm 9593, which environmental laws and rules will be included in that commitment.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","163775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940643","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-07-19","<p>The UK is a global leader in the fight against climate change. Our ambitious agenda is set out in domestic law, and our commitments are more stretching than those that arise from our current obligations under EU law. The UK will maintain these high standards after withdrawal.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>We recognise the UK’s and the EU’s shared interest in global action on climate change, and the mutual benefits of a broad agreement on climate change cooperation. The exact details of this will be subject to negotiation.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2018-07-19T15:05:23.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940643/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940643/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940643/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-07-13","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 108(d) of the White Paper, The future relationship between the UK and the EU, Cm 9593, which laws and rules on climate change will be included in the non-regression commitment.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","163776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940644","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-07-19","<p>The UK has an impressive record of protecting consumers and has been clear in the White Paper that it wishes to commit to maintaining high standards of consumer protection after we leave the EU. We believe the EU should make a reciprocal commitment, the exact details of which will be subject to negotiation.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2018-07-19T15:06:20.15Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940644/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940644/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940644/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-07-13","Consumers: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union,with reference to paragraph 108(f) of the White Paper, The future relationship between the UK and the EU, Cm 9593, which laws and rules on consumer protection will be included in that commitment.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","163777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940645","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-07-18","<p>The negotiations on our future relationship with the EU are ongoing and the structure of any future UK-EU system of social security coordination is subject to these negotiations. As the White Paper notes, the UK will seek reciprocal arrangements on the future rules around some defined elements of social security coordination. This will be important for UK nationals who want to live, work or retire in the EU in the future, as part of our new arrangements. This could cover provisions for the uprating of state pensions, including export rules and accompanying aggregation principles for people who have contributed into multiple countries’ systems. It would also ensure workers only pay social security contributions in one state at a time. There should be reciprocal healthcare cover for state pensioners retiring to the EU or the UK, continued participation in the EHIC scheme and cooperation on planned medical treatment. This would be supported by any necessary administrative cooperation and data-sharing requirements</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-07-18T14:45:45.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940645/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940645/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940645/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-07-13","Social Security Benefits: Reciprocal Arrangements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to paragraph 89 of the White Paper, The future relationship between the UK and the EU, Cm 9593, which benefits will be included in the proposals for coordination of welfare systems.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","163778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940646","Home Office","false","2018-07-18","<p>The Government is considering a range of options for the future borders and immigration system, and will set out further details later this year. Free movement will end and we will control immigration in the national interest.The current Immigration Rules allow visitors to come to the UK for up to 6 months in the UK and list the permitted activities which a visitor may do.</p><p>Recognising the depth of the UK-EU relationship, the UK will make a sovereign choice to seek reciprocal mobility arrangements with the EU covering visits for short-term business reasons, and specific allowed activities will be part of that discussion.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","163780","2018-07-18T13:56:07.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940646/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940646/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940646/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-07-13","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to paragraph 76(b) of the White Paper, The future relationship between the UK and the EU, Cm 9593, what the maximum duration of a visa-free visit will be for temporary business activity.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","163779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940647","Home Office","false","2018-07-18","<p>The Government is considering a range of options for the future borders and immigration system, and will set out further details later this year. Free movement will end and we will control immigration in the national interest.The current Immigration Rules allow visitors to come to the UK for up to 6 months in the UK and list the permitted activities which a visitor may do.</p><p>Recognising the depth of the UK-EU relationship, the UK will make a sovereign choice to seek reciprocal mobility arrangements with the EU covering visits for short-term business reasons, and specific allowed activities will be part of that discussion.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","163779","2018-07-18T13:56:07.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940647/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940647/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940647/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-07-13","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to paragraph 76(b) of the White Paper, The future relationship between the UK and the EU, Cm 9593, what activities will be included in the classification temporary business activity.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","163780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940648","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-07-20","<p>The Government takes the issue of consumer product safety seriously and is committed to ensuring that only safe products are placed on the UK market now and in the future. This includes a robust programme of risk-based market surveillance. This market surveillance programme will continue to include the ability to intercept products as they enter the UK, check products already on the market, and gather information through a variety of intelligence sources.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-07-20T13:42:11.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940648/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940648/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940648/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-07-13","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to paragraph 44 of the White Paper, The future relationship between the UK and the EU, Cm 9593, what (a) government and (b) regulatory activities will be included in the programme of risk-based market surveillance.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","163781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940649","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-07-24","<p>As set out in the White Paper, we are proposing a UK-EU free trade area for goods, underpinned by an upfront commitment to a common rulebook on goods, including agri-food, and a Facilitated Customs Arrangement to avoid customs checks and controls at our borders.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In the case of manufactured goods, this encompasses all rules that could be checked at the border, as they set the requirements for placing manufactured goods on the market. For agricultural products, food and drink, this includes relevant Sanitary and Phytosanitary (SPS) rules, but excludes those which relate to wider food policy or domestic production.</p>","Fareham","Suella Braverman",,"2018-07-24T15:55:42.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940649/answer","Biography information for Suella Braverman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940649/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940649/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-07-13","Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 7(a) of the White Paper, The future relationship between the UK and the EU, Cm 9593, which rules will be included in the category of  necessary to provide frictionless trade at the border.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","163782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940650","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-07-26","<p>In areas where the UK had committed to maintain a common rulebook with the EU, the Joint Committee would need to agree on whether a proposed EU rule change should be incorporated into the agreements, and there would be a process for the UK Parliament to be consulted on this. If the UK and the EU could not agree, the Joint Committee should consider all other possibilities and endeavour to maintain the functioning of the relevant agreement, including the possibility to recognise the equivalence of legislation. If this was not possible after a defined period and an imbalance was created, proportionate and where possible localised rebalancing measures could be proposed, for instance, requesting financial compensation. Where there was no agreement over these measures, or they were not possible, the relevant part of the future relationship could be suspended</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In areas where there is a common rulebook, there could be proportionate implications for the operation of the future relationship from the decisions taken by Parliament about what legislation it chooses to adopt in the future. For instance, if the UK and the EU had agreed to add a rule change to the agreements, and if the UK Parliament decided not to give effect to this change in domestic law, it would be in the knowledge that it would breach the UK's international obligations, and that the EU could raise a dispute and ultimately impose non-compliance measures on the UK. As set out in the White Paper, the type of measures that could be imposed for different sorts of breaches would be technical, but could include financial penalties or suspension of specific obligations.</p>","Fareham","Suella Braverman",,"2018-07-26T13:42:00.803Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940650/answer","Biography information for Suella Braverman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940650/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940650/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-07-13","UK Relations with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 5 of the White Paper, The future relationship between the UK and the EU,  Cm 9593, what the proportionate implications will be for the operation of the future relationship.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","163783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940651","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-07-18","<p>The Big White Wall (BWW), a digital support and recovery service, was established in 2007 not specifically for Service personnel and veterans but for the wider population suffering with mental health problems.</p><p> </p><p>The decision to contract for the BWW services was made following the publication in 2010 of Dr Andrew Murrison MD MP’s ‘Fighting Fit’ report. The Ministry of Defence (MOD) fund the Service personnel spaces on the online mental wellbeing website provided by the BWW, while the Department for Health and Social Care fund access for veterans and families of serving personnel.</p><p> </p><p>The MOD has contributed the following payments to the BWW in the financial years shown:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Amount (£) excluding VAT</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>73,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>75,600</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>100,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>91,100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>35,745</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>26,250</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The MOD payment to the BWW is expected to continue for the near future, dependent on whether serving personnel still require access to the BWW or if they have access to other support.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has funded the Veterans Gateway through the Covenant Fund, which ran a grants programme to award a single grant to a pilot project to create the Veterans Gateway. A £2 million grant was awarded to a consortium of charities led by The Royal British Legion. A further £200,000 was awarded to support a university-led evaluation of this pilot project and to support activities to improve the reach of the Veterans Gateway.</p><p> </p><p>The Covenant Fund provision for the Veterans Gateway was provided in order to help establish the Veterans Gateway and cover the start-up costs. This was made with the explicit understanding of all the charities involved that this grant would be a one-off payment. We strongly support the work of the Veterans Gateway; however, there are currently no plans for the MOD to provide regular funding.</p><p> </p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","163771","2018-07-18T15:52:48.34Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940651/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940651/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940651/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-07-13","Armed Forces: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much funding he has allocated and how he has allocated it to the (a) Big White Wall and (b) Veterans' Gateway projects in each year since their inception; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","163770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/940652","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-07-18","<p>The Big White Wall (BWW), a digital support and recovery service, was established in 2007 not specifically for Service personnel and veterans but for the wider population suffering with mental health problems.</p><p> </p><p>The decision to contract for the BWW services was made following the publication in 2010 of Dr Andrew Murrison MD MP’s ‘Fighting Fit’ report. The Ministry of Defence (MOD) fund the Service personnel spaces on the online mental wellbeing website provided by the BWW, while the Department for Health and Social Care fund access for veterans and families of serving personnel.</p><p> </p><p>The MOD has contributed the following payments to the BWW in the financial years shown:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Amount (£) excluding VAT</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>73,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>75,600</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>100,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>91,100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>35,745</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>26,250</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The MOD payment to the BWW is expected to continue for the near future, dependent on whether serving personnel still require access to the BWW or if they have access to other support.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has funded the Veterans Gateway through the Covenant Fund, which ran a grants programme to award a single grant to a pilot project to create the Veterans Gateway. A £2 million grant was awarded to a consortium of charities led by The Royal British Legion. A further £200,000 was awarded to support a university-led evaluation of this pilot project and to support activities to improve the reach of the Veterans Gateway.</p><p> </p><p>The Covenant Fund provision for the Veterans Gateway was provided in order to help establish the Veterans