"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939923","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-17","<p>The May 2018 Amnesty International report on Nicaragua is alarming. We continue to follow developments closely, including through contacts with EU and US partners and local stakeholders in the country. We have expressed our deep concern about the violence to the Nicaraguan government and urged them to take responsibility for ending the repression against their own citizens.</p><p>We welcome the work of international institutions in Nicaragua, such as the UN and Organisation of American States (OAS) and I welcome the government's invitations to the Inter American Commission on Human Rights, the UN, and the EU to support the resolution of the crisis and urge the authorities to allow them to carry out their work fully without hindrance.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-07-17T14:35:29.83Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939923/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939923/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939923/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-07-12","Nicaragua: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the report, Nicaragua: Shoot to kill: Nicaragua's strategy to repress protest, published by Amnesty International in May 2018.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","163552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939924","Treasury","false","2018-07-19","<p>Goods entering the UK under the ISO code ‘EH’ are chargeable to customs duty.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-07-19T15:58:49.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939924/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939924/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939924/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-07-12","Import Duties: Western Sahara","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 27 June 2018 to Question 158255, on Western Sahara: Imports, whether products entering the UK under the ISO code EH pay import duty.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","163555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939925","Treasury","false","2018-07-19","<p>I refer the hon. Member to my answer of 6 July to PQ UIN 158256. It is for the European Commission to respond to any questions about its report.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-07-19T16:01:03.723Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939925/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939925/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939925/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-07-12","Import Duties: Western Sahara","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 6 July 2018 to Question 158255, on Import Duties: Western Sahara, for what reasons the Western Sahara Campaign UK is included in the list of consultees when it states that it was not consulted.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","163556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939926","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-07-18","<p>The Government-mandated tariff, WaterSure, is in place to support customers on low incomes who have unavoidably high water usage, due to either a qualifying medical condition or having three or more children under 19. Eligible customers must be on a water meter and in receipt of a means tested benefit, and they or someone living in the household must have the qualifying medical condition. This includes Crohn’s. All water companies must offer the tariff.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Water bills are rigorously safeguarded by Ofwat, the industry’s independent economic regulator, through five-yearly price reviews, which set an overall cap on the total amount that each water company may recover from their customers. Ofwat expects the average real water and sewerage bill to fall 5% from 2015 - 2020, and potentially up to 10% by 2025.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government’s 2017 <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/661803/sps-ofwat-2017.pdf" target="_blank">strategic policy statement</a> to Ofwat challenged the water industry to do more for vulnerable customers.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","163558","2018-07-18T14:18:26.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939926/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939926/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939926/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-07-12","Water Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he has made an assessment of the (a) potential effect of increased water rates on people with (i) Chrones and (ii) similar conditions who use more water than the average household and (b) requirement to put in place plans for those people in the event of such an increase; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","163557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939927","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-19","<p>The Government is considering the responses received to the recently closed consultation on the effectiveness of the powers to deal with unauthorised developments and encampments. The consultation touched on a broad range of issues, which included the provision of uthorised sites, and the impact on settled and travelling communities. The Government wants to understand the issues in more depth before deciding what action to take in response to stakeholders' views. The Secretary of State and I have had discussions with interested parties, including Members of Parliament, and continue to listen closely to stakeholders' views to ensure a robust and proportionate Government response.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-07-19T16:07:11.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939927/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939927/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939927/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-07-12","Travellers: Caravan Sites","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with the Housing Minister on the findings of the Race Disparity Audit in relation to accommodation for Gypsies and Travellers and the Government review, Powers for dealing with unauthorised development and encampments.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","163553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939928","Department for Education","false","2018-07-20","<p>We are providing supplementary funding of around £60 million a year to enable local authorities to protect maintained nursery school (MNS) funding until 2019-20. It is for local authorities to set the rates paid to maintained nursery schools. This supplementary funding provides MNS with stability whilst we develop a long-term solution for them. An important part of this will be understanding the value for money that they offer, and new research will report on this later in the year.</p><p>MNS also benefit from our increased hourly rates paid to local authorities to deliver the 15 hour free entitlement for disadvantaged two-year-olds. From April 2017, all local authorities saw 7% increases in their funding rates for two-year-olds.</p><p>Future funding decisions after 2019-20 will be set at the next spending review.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","163604 ; 163606","2018-07-20T13:23:39.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939928/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939928/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939928/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-07-12","Pre-school Education: Per Capita Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of funding per child in maintained nursery schools.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","163603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939929","Department for Education","false","2018-07-20","<p>We are providing supplementary funding of around £60 million a year to enable local authorities to protect maintained nursery school (MNS) funding until 2019-20. It is for local authorities to set the rates paid to maintained nursery schools. This supplementary funding provides MNS with stability whilst we develop a long-term solution for them. An important part of this will be understanding the value for money that they offer, and new research will report on this later in the year.</p><p>MNS also benefit from our increased hourly rates paid to local authorities to deliver the 15 hour free entitlement for disadvantaged two-year-olds. From April 2017, all local authorities saw 7% increases in their funding rates for two-year-olds.</p><p>Future funding decisions after 2019-20 will be set at the next spending review.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","163603 ; 163606","2018-07-20T13:23:39.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939929/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939929/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939929/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-07-12","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether the level of free childcare funding per two-year-old in maintained nursery schools has risen in line with inflation.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","163604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939930","Department for Education","false","2018-07-20","<p>We have commissioned an independent evaluation of the first year of 30 hours delivery, which will be published this summer. We will use the evidence from this evaluation and the learnings from the first year of delivery to inform the future eligibility and delivery of 30 hours.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-07-20T13:25:35.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939930/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939930/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939930/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-07-12","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether he has made an assessment of the potential merits of reviewing eligibility for 30-hours free childcare annually; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","163605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939931","Department for Education","false","2018-07-20","<p>We are providing supplementary funding of around £60 million a year to enable local authorities to protect maintained nursery school (MNS) funding until 2019-20. It is for local authorities to set the rates paid to maintained nursery schools. This supplementary funding provides MNS with stability whilst we develop a long-term solution for them. An important part of this will be understanding the value for money that they offer, and new research will report on this later in the year.</p><p>MNS also benefit from our increased hourly rates paid to local authorities to deliver the 15 hour free entitlement for disadvantaged two-year-olds. From April 2017, all local authorities saw 7% increases in their funding rates for two-year-olds.</p><p>Future funding decisions after 2019-20 will be set at the next spending review.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","163603 ; 163604","2018-07-20T13:23:39.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939931/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939931/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939931/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-07-12","Pre-school Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether his Department provides support for maintained nurseries to formulate their three-year budgets beyond 2020.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","163606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939932","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-07-20","<p>We have made no such estimate. Claimants currently only migrate from existing benefits to Universal Credit following a relevant change of circumstance that would previously have prompted a new claim to another existing benefit. Therefore it is not possible to estimate with accuracy when such changes may occur.</p><p> </p><p>We will start to move legacy benefit claimants to Universal Credit as part of our Managed Migration process from July 2019. At this point, claimants will receive transitional protection if their overall Universal Credit entitlement would be less than under the old system, provided that their circumstances remain the same.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-07-20T11:34:08.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939932/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939932/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939932/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-07-12","Child Tax Credit: Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate her Department has made of the number of students receiving child tax credits and who will be transferred to universal credit this year in (a) Scotland and (b) the UK; and what assessment she has made of changes in the level of funding for those students.","false","Biography information for Lesley Laird","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Lesley Laird","163623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939933","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-17","<p>​I refer the Hon. Member to the Financial Secretary to the Treasury’s recent answer to a similar question regarding imports from Western Sahara (158256).</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-07-17T16:40:42.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939933/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939933/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939933/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-07-12","Western Sahara: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the implications of the judgment of the European Court of Justice in cases C-104/16 P Council V Front Polisario and C-266/16 Western Sahara Campaign UK for his policies on the territory of, and products originating from, Western Sahara.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","163610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939934","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-17","<p>The UK accepts the judgement of the European Court of Justice in these cases, and has always been clear that any new proposals to the Council which address the substance of the judgement should conform with international law.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-07-17T16:41:51.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939934/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939934/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939934/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-07-12","Western Sahara: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the implications of the judgment of the European Court of Justice in cases C-104/16 P Council V Front Polisario and C-266/16 Western Sahara Campaign UK for the recent trade proposals to the European Council of Ministers.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","163611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939935","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-18","<p>I met the Cameroonian Commonwealth Minister Mbayu and the then Foreign Secretary met Prime Minister Yang at the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting in April. We both pressed for action to resolve the ongoing dispute in the Anglophone regions and for adherence to core Commonwealth values and principles, including tolerance, respect and understanding.</p><p>The UK ensured that the European Union Statement at the Human Rights Council meeting, in Geneva in June, included a call for access to the Anglophone regions of Cameroon for the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights (UNHCHR). We also welcomed the statement by the UNHCHR, Zeid Ra'ad Al Hussein, at that meeting, in which he called for the Cameroonian authorities swiftly to approve a mission by his Office to all parts of the country. We will continue to work with international partners and through Ministerial engagement and our High Commission in Yaoundé to urge the Cameroonians to allow UNHCHR unhindered access.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-07-18T15:38:23.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939935/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939935/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939935/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-07-12","Cameroon: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will help secure access to British Southern Cameroons territory for the office of the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","163505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939936","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-07-18","<p>The Government-mandated tariff, WaterSure, is in place to support customers on low incomes who have unavoidably high water usage, due to either a qualifying medical condition or having three or more children under 19. Eligible customers must be on a water meter and in receipt of a means tested benefit, and they or someone living in the household must have the qualifying medical condition. This includes Crohn’s. All water companies must offer the tariff.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Water bills are rigorously safeguarded by Ofwat, the industry’s independent economic regulator, through five-yearly price reviews, which set an overall cap on the total amount that each water company may recover from their customers. Ofwat expects the average real water and sewerage bill to fall 5% from 2015 - 2020, and potentially up to 10% by 2025.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government’s 2017 <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/661803/sps-ofwat-2017.pdf" target="_blank">strategic policy statement</a> to Ofwat challenged the water industry to do more for vulnerable customers.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","163557","2018-07-18T14:18:26.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939936/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939936/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939936/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-07-12","Water Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he is planning for an increase in water rates; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","163558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939937","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-07-17","<p>The eCommerce Directive is EU legislation. As detailed in the Withdrawal Agreement, EU law will remain in place until the end of the Implementation Period. There are no plans to publish proposals to modernise the eCommerce Directive.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-07-17T10:00:19.07Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939937/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939937/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939937/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-07-12","Electronic Commerce: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, when he plans to publish proposals to modernise the eCommerce directive.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","163522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939938","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-07-19","<p>No recent assessment has been made.</p><p> </p><p>On 28 June 2018, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) published a new Quality Standard (QS) on spondyloarthritis. The QS includes four quality statements identified as the markers of high quality spondyloarthritis care. QSs are important in setting out to patients, the public, commissioners and providers what a high quality service should look like in a particular area of care. Whilst providers and commissioners must have regard to NICE QSs in planning and delivering services, they do not provide a comprehensive service specification and are not mandatory.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-07-19T15:13:17.933Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939938/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939938/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939938/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-07-12","Spondyloarthritis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of a widespread adoption of the NICE Quality Standard on Spondyloarthritis.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","163635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939939","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-07-17","<p>Following its announcement in the Spring 2017 Budget, the LFFN programme invested £10m in market trials of its full fibre stimulation approach across the country.</p><p> </p><p>After evaluation of these trials, in November 2017 LFFN launched its £190m Challenge Fund, designed to stimulate commercial investment in full fibre networks in both rural and urban locations across the whole of the UK. Local bodies were invited to submit formal bids, and the first round of funding was allocated to 13 successful bidders that were announced in the Chancellor’s Spring Statement in March 2018.</p><p> </p><p>In March 2018 LFFN also delivered on a manifesto commitment with the launch of its £67m Gigabit Broadband Voucher Scheme for small to medium sized businesses and the local communities around them across the UK.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-07-17T10:05:31.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939939/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939939/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939939/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-07-12","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what progress his Department is making on the implementation of the Local Full Fibre Networks programme, announced in Spring Budget 2017.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","163585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939940","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-07-17","<p>The LFFN programme has engaged regularly with Scottish government officials on the overall programme and on specific initiatives, and collaborated with Scottish Government to run a joint regional event in December 2017 for Scottish Local Authorities, advising them how to bid into the £190m Challenge Fund. We are also in regular discussion with the Scottish Government around the R100 Programme, to ensure alignment between our programmes.</p><p> </p><p>LFFN is delivering significant benefits in Scotland. Aberdeen and Aberdeenshire was selected as a pilot areas ahead of the launch of the £67m Gigabit Broadband Voucher Scheme. The Highlands of Scotland were one of the successful bidders announced in the Chancellor’s Spring Statement in 2018, and we are also currently in communication with several Scottish Local Authorities regarding their interest in bidding for the next round of the Challenge Fund.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-07-17T10:06:42.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939940/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939940/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939940/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-07-12","Broadband: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions his Department has had with the Scottish Government on the Local Full Fibre Networks programme, announced in Spring Budget 2017.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","163586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939941","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-07-17","<p>I refer the honourable member to the answer of PQ 150069. This is a matter for the Home Office.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-07-17T16:54:32.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939941/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939941/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939941/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-07-12","Ministry of Justice: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he plans to respond to Question 150069, on CCTV recordings, tabled by the hon. Member for Scunthorpe on 4 June 2018.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","163551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939942","Home Office","false","2018-07-17","<p>Home Office Ministers and officials meet regularly with Refugee Action and other NGOs to discuss the operation of the asylum system. However, we do not routinely provide responses to individual reports.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-07-17T16:30:00.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939942/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939942/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939942/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-07-12","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if he will make an assessment of the implications for his policies of the report Waiting in the Dark: How the asylum system dehumanises, disempowers and damages, published in May 2018 by Refugee Action.","false","Biography information for Faisal Rashid","Warrington South","Faisal Rashid","163629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939943","Home Office","false","2018-07-17","<p>UK Visas and Immigration has an internal audit process, consisting of reviews by senior case workers and independent auditors, which assesses the application of Home Office policy. We continue to work to improve the quality of decision-making to ensure that we properly consider all the evidence provided and get decisions right the first time.</p><p>Appeals are allowed for a variety of reasons including the presentation of fresh evidence, not available at the time of the initial decision. We have a very active feedback system between our presenting officers and those who make decisions on asylum claims. Where our reviews show that there are lessons for the Home Office, these are fed back to decision making units who use them to improve operational practices.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-07-17T16:27:13.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939943/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939943/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939943/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-07-12","Asylum: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference evidence in the report, Waiting in the Dark: How the asylum system dehumanises, disempowers and damages, published by Refugee Action in May 2019, what assessment has he made of the reasons for the high number of decisions overturned on appeal.","false","Biography information for Faisal Rashid","Warrington South","Faisal Rashid","163630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939944","Treasury","false","2018-07-18","<p>The latest figures from the Office for National Statistics figures show that in 2017, overall manufacturing investment grew by 3.1% and car sales were 25% higher than in 2010. The automotive sector is a valuable part of the UK economy and the government has recently established the first automotive sector deal. Through mechanisms such as the Advanced Propulsion Centre, we have approved R&amp;D projects worth £680 million with £322 million of Government investment.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-07-18T15:03:23.283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939944/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939944/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939944/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-07-12","Motor Vehicles: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the reductions in the level of investment in the UK car industry in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Faisal Rashid","Warrington South","Faisal Rashid","163631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939945","Home Office","false","2018-07-17","<p>The Home Office publish data on the number of children entering detention by year and quarter. The data is available in tables dt_02 and dt_02_q of the detention tables.</p><p>The latest available data are published in ‘Immigration Statistics, year ending March 2018’ at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/709326/detention-mar-2018-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/709326/detention-mar-2018-tables.ods</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-07-17T16:11:17.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939945/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939945/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939945/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-07-12","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many children have been detained in Immigration Removal Centres in each year for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","163532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939946","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-17","<p>The Department does not hold information on the number of victims of domestic abuse who have slept rough and experienced homelessness in each of the last five years.</p><p>However, we know that in 2017/18, 1,330 households were accepted as homeless with the primary reason of acceptance being that they were vulnerable as a result of having fled their home because of domestic violence or the threat of domestic violence. These statistics are available for each local authority area, and previous years at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-homelessness#detailed-local-authority-level-responses" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-homelessness#detailed-local-authority-level-responses</a></p><p>Domestic abuse is a devastating crime that nobody should have to suffer. Supporting victims of domestic abuse is an absolute priority for this Government. Councils have a legal duty to provide accommodation to families and others who are vulnerable as a result of fleeing domestic abuse. The Homelessness Reduction Act requires councils to take reasonable steps for all eligible households who are homeless, to help them secure accommodation.</p><p>We are overhauling the statutory homelessness data collection alongside the introduction of the Homelessness Reduction Act. This will give us better insights into the causes of homelessness and the support people need, including where someone is accepted as homeless because they were vulnerable as a result of having fled their home because of domestic violence or the threat of domestic violence, alongside other reasons for acceptance.</p><p>We are also continuing to support the Women’s Aid Routes to Support and No Woman Turned Away projects, having already provided almost £889,000 between 2015 and 2018 for these projects. Routes to Support (formerly UK Refuges online) is part-funded by the Government and is a UK-wide online database containing information about domestic abuse and other violence against women services. No Woman Turned Away provides caseworker support to women facing difficulties in accessing refuge, including those at risk of or who have been sleeping rough or experiencing homelessness.</p><p>We have also commissioned an audit of domestic abuse service delivery - being run by Ipsos MORI – to give us a picture of provision across England, enabling us to understand what impact services are having and to identify gaps in provision.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams",,"2018-07-17T16:34:48.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939946/answer","Biography information for Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939946/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939946/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-07-12","Homelessness: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of victims of domestic abuse who have (a) slept rough and (b) experienced homelessness in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","163484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939947","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-19","<p>The Department does not collect information on the number of households registered as statutorily overcrowded. However, we do collect information on overcrowding more generally. The Department's English Housing Survey collects information on overcrowding (measured using the Bedroom Standard). Statistics for England are published annually.</p><p>See Annex Table 1.20 here: <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/676433/2016-17_Section_1_Households_Annex_Tables.xlsx" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/676433/2016-17_Section_1_Households_Annex_Tables.xlsx</a></p><p>The Department's Local Authority Housing Statistics collects information on the number of households on a local authority housing waiting list because they are currently residing in insanitary or overcrowded housing, see here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2016-to-2017</a></p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-07-19T15:06:03.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939947/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939947/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939947/answer","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939947/answer/previousversion/70155","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-07-12","Housing: Overcrowding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many households were registered as statutorily overcrowded in (a) Camberwell and Peckham, (b) Southwark and (c) London in each of the last 5 years.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","163485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939948","Department for Transport","false","2018-07-17","<p>The Department for Transport does not routinely hold this information, but I have asked Govia Thameslink Railway to provide it to the Rt Hon and Learned Member directly.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-07-17T15:54:39.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939948/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939948/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939948/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-07-12","Nunhead Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many trains per hour stopped at Nunhead train station in June in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","163486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939949","Department for Transport","false","2018-07-17","<p>The performance of the Thameslink timetable through Camberwell and Peckham since 20 May has been unacceptable. As of 15 July, Govia Thameslink Railway have put in place an amended timetable which must provide passengers with the performance they expect.</p><p> </p><p>Southern Metro services through Camberwell and Peckham (which are also run by Govia Thameslink Railway) have been performing very well and we expect this to continue.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-07-17T15:47:17.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939949/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939949/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939949/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-07-12","Govia Thameslink Railway: Timetables","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the introduction of the new Govia Thameslink timetable in Camberwell and Peckham.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","163487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939950","Department for Transport","false","2018-07-17","<p>The review of the Govia Thameslink franchise is continuing and will report to the Secretary of State in the coming weeks.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-07-17T15:44:17.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939950/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939950/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939950/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-07-12","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 4 July 2018 to Question 158209 on Govia Thameslink Railway, when his Department plans to conclude its review on whether Govia Thameslink Railway has met their contractual obligations.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","163488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939951","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-07-17","<p>The National Prison Healthcare Board for England was established by the Ministry of Justice in 2013. Separate arrangements exist for Wales.</p><p>The Board oversees the National Partnership for Prison Healthcare in England 2018-2021 at official level and Ministers do not therefore attend. Separate arrangements exist for the briefing of Ministers on relevant issues.</p><p>Since 2013, the Board has met approximately every three months. Information on the number of officials attending the National Prison Healthcare Board for England is not held centrally. Therefore obtaining this information would be at disproportionate cost.</p><p>The Deputy Director for Mental Health Justice and Legislation is a permanent member of the National Prison Healthcare Board; other officials from the Department of Health and Social Care may attend when required.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","163543","2018-07-17T17:05:43.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939951/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939951/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939951/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-07-12","National Prison Healthcare Board","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, when the National Prison Healthcare Board was created; how many times that Board has met; and how many times (a) Ministers and (b) officials from his Department have attended meetings of that Board.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","163540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939952","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-07-18","<p>The mental health policy team in the Department works flexibly across a wide range of policy priorities, including healthcare for offenders in prison and in the community. Additionally, there are a range of other teams within the Department whose policy responsibilities have implications for prison healthcare. It is therefore not possible to say how many officials work exclusively on prison healthcare.</p><p>Information on how many Departmental officials have made visits to prisons in the last 12 months can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p>I have Ministerial responsibility for offender healthcare, which includes healthcare in prisons and secure hospitals. I am planning to complete my round of visits to all high secure hospitals in England shortly with a visit to Rampton Secure Hospital, having already visited Broadmoor and Ashworth Secure Hospitals. Effective treatment in the community is an important means of reducing offending and reoffending behaviour, I therefore also have plans to visit a women’s centre and liaison and diversion services, as well as a prison, in the near future.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","163542 ; 163544","2018-07-18T16:38:13.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939952/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939952/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939952/answer","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/939952/answer/previousversion/70191","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-07-12","Prisons: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many officials from his Department work exclusively on prison healthcare.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","163541"
